my:Hazard.my:ControlMeasures:
a) Operation to be planned and carried out by a competent person(s); 
b) The Master or Chief Officer must be and remain in overall charge of the operation; 
c) All crew involved to be briefed and have the necessary training and understanding; 
d) Ensure that there is sufficient stability at all times during the operation; 
e) Crew vigilance - Constant monitoring of the task; 
f) Ballast operations to be carried out in line with the operation; 
g) Consult 'Cargo Loading / Discharging Operation' Risk Assessment, if necessary.

a) The Master or Chief Officer must be and remain in overall charge of the operation; 
b) Assess the load to be lifted, taking into account any information that may be provided; 
c) All lifting appliances should be checked to confirm that it is appropriate in strength and design for the load; 
d) Be aware that the centre of gravity may differ from the geometrical centre of the load; 
e) Ensure the load will pass clear of the vessel's structure i.e. accommodation, crane columns, etc.; 
f) Lines should be fitted to the load to allow control of any rotational movement; 
g) When the load is lifted, if it is found that the weight is in excess of that declared or the centre of gravity is incorrect so that the lifting points are incorrectly positioned, the operation should be abandoned and the load returned to the quay / cargo hold;
h) Consult 'Crane Operation' Risk Assessment, if necessary; 
i) Consult 'Cargo Loading / Discharging Operation' Risk Assessment, if necessary.

a) The Master or Chief Officer must be and remain in overall charge of the operation; 
b) All crew involved to be briefed and have the necessary training and understanding; 
c) Only experienced and fully trained crew are to operate the cargo crane; 
d) Adequate lighting to be provided; 
e) Communication must be established, via VHF or crane signals, between the crane operators and assisting crew; 
f) The signalman should be placed in an appropriate position; 
g) The weight of the load must be equally distributed between both cranes; 
h) The hoisting / swinging of both cranes should be steady and controlled; 
i) Particular attention should be paid to when one or both cranes are operating close to their outreach limit.

a) All crew involved to be briefed and have a full understanding of signal procedures; 
b) VHF radio check prior to operations; 
c) Use of the English language in clear and concise orders; 
d) Use of headphones in conjunction with the VHF.
